 Aboubacar, Awa, Fatou, Idrissa, Matar, Moctar, Oumou.","Scottish or Irish: shortened form of   McFall  .","English: topographic name, Middle English <i>fal(le)</i> ‘fall, descent’ (from Old English <i>(ge)feall</i> or <i>(ge)fall</i> ‘felling of trees’, Old Norse <i>fall</i> ‘forest clearing’), denoting a waterfall, steep slope, or (in northern England) a forest clearing."],"variants":[{"name":"Faull","meanings":["English: variant of   Fall  .","Irish: variant of   Faul  .","German: variant of   Faul  . The surname <i>Faull</i> is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"McFall","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   McPhail  . This is the most usual Irish Anglicization."]},{"name":"Fallis","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>faleise</i>, <i>faloise</i> ‘cliff’ (a word of ancient Germanic origin), for someone who lived on or by a cliff. Or from Falaise in Calvados, France, which was the birthplace of William the Conqueror.","English: variant of   Fall   2.","Scottish and northern Irish: shortened form of   McFalls   (see also   McPhail  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Olaf  , also widely used in southwest Sweden."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert de la Vall was born in 1257, in Normandy, France. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Jane de Pritot. He died in 1296, in his hometown, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1257–1296":"1257–1296","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1257":"1257","1286":"1286","1296":"1296","about 1286":"umbes 1286","1270":"1270","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Callander, Stirling, Scotland":"Callander, Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1257–1296":"1257–1296","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","1257":"1257","1286":"1286","1296":"1296","about 1286":"noin 1286","1270":"1270","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Callander, Stirling, Scotland":"Callander, Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1257–1296":"1257–1296","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1286–Female":"1286–Décédée","1257":"1257","1286":"1286","1296":"1296","about 1286":"environ 1286","1270":"1270","Normandy, France":"Normandie, France","Callander, Stirling, Scotland":"Callander, Stirlingshire, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Sir Robert de la Vall est né en 1257, à Normandie, France. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Lady Jane de Pritot. Il est décédé en 1296, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 39 ans."},"de":{"1257–1296":"1257–1296","1270–Female":"1270–Verstorben","1286–Female":"1286–Verstorben","1257":"1257","1286":"1286","1296":"1296","about 1286":"um 1286","1270":"1270","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankreich","Callander, Stirling, Scotland":"Callander, Stirlingshir